Vittorio Valletta (28 July 1883 in Sampierdarena – 10 August 1967 in Foccette di Pietrasanta) was an Italian industrialist and President of [MASK] from 1946 to 1966.

Born at Sampierdarena, near Genoa, Valletta was a lecturer in economics before he joined [MASK] in April 1921: as a result of his academic qualifications and background he was often known to colleagues and in the trade as "Il Professore".

He presided during two decades of rapid expansion as small Fiats proliferated on Italian streets, and he lived out the injunction of the company's founder to "make [MASK] greater, giving more working opportunities to the people, and producing better and cheaper cars".
Valletta continued as Chairman of [MASK] until, at the age of 83, he retired in April 1966 to be succeeded in that post by the founder's grandson, Dr. Giovanni Agnelli.
The Italian president's citation described Valletta as "the first [MASK] worker, and one of the great men who most contributed to the Italian economic miracle and to the welfare of the country".
